The U.S-Japan Joint Statement on the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) reaffirms the commitment of both countries to seek a world without nuclear weapons and to the NPT. They aim to strengthen each of the Treaty's three pillars: nuclear disarmament, nuclear non-proliferation, and peaceful uses of nuclear energy. The statement highlights the catastrophic consequences of nuclear weapons use and emphasizes the importance of preventing their use through disarmament efforts. Both countries support a step-by-step approach to nuclear disarmament and call for further progress in reducing nuclear weapons. They also support the principles of irreversibility, verifiability, and transparency in disarmament and non-proliferation efforts. The statement acknowledges the positive role played by civil society and supports access to nuclear technology and energy for peaceful purposes. The United States and Japan pledge financial support to the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) Peaceful Uses Initiative. They call on all states to adhere to IAEA safeguards agreements and emphasize the importance of addressing challenges to the NPT posed by cases of noncompliance. The statement welcomes the EU/E3+3 deal with Iran and encourages the completion of work to resolve concerns about Iran's nuclear program. It also reiterates the commitment to achieve North Korea's denuclearization and urges North Korea to honor its commitments. The statement underscores the importance of promoting stringent export control and enhancing export control capacity in Asia and globally.